			<div class="cd-timeline-content">	
			<h2>Birth</h2>	<br>	
				<p>Australian Brian Smith founded UGG with $500 in start-up funds in Southern California in 1978 to sell sheepskin shearling boots. The Aussie style was originally designed to help <a href="http://www.news.com.au/world/ugg-man-happy-to-trade-dollars-for-surf/story-e6frfkyi-1226006046295" target="_blank">surfers</a> to combat chilly weather.</p>
				<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e5/Uggs2.jpg">
				<div class="photocap">A pair of UGG boots, via Wikimedia Commons</div>	
				<span class="cd-date"><h2>1978</h2></span>
			</div> <!-- cd-timeline-content -->
			
		</div> <!-- cd-timeline-block -->


<!--new box-->
		<div class="cd-timeline-block">
			<div class="cd-timeline-img cd-location">
				<img src="img/cd-icon-location.svg" alt="Location">
			</div> <!-- cd-timeline-img -->
			
			<div class="cd-timeline-content">
			<h2>Fall under big umbrella</h2>
			<p>
			California-based Deckers Outdoor Corporation acquired UGG for $14.6 million in 1995 and expanded it into an international brand. During the late 90s, UGG experienced double-digit sales growth. </p>
			
			<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/75/Ugg_boots.jpg">
			<div class="photocap">UGG boots, via Wikimedia Commons</div>
			<span class="cd-date"><h2>1995</h2></span>
			</div>
		</div>
<!--end new box-->
